This operator is made for accessing deep nest values.

&lt;s&gt;Let&#39;s look at `document.getElementById(&#39;output&#39;)?.innerHTML`. This will return `undefined` (if &#39;#output&#39; not exists) or `string` (if &#39;#output&#39; exists). And you trying to assign `string` to it.&lt;/s&gt;

Here you are trying to set value of property of object, that may be not exists.

So yep, optional property access can not be used at the left-hand side of an assignment.

You can read more about it in [proposal][1]


  [1]: https://github.com/tc39/proposal-optional-chaining

